  "notes": "Proto-Northwest Germanic (~1st c. CE). The common ancestor of all North and West Germanic languages, after the separation of East Germanic (Gothic branch). KEY INNOVATION: Rhotacism — PGmc *z → NW Gmc *r (word-finally and intervocalically). Gothic preserves *z; all NW Gmc descendants have r in these positions. Evidence: OE hār, ON hárr, OHG hār 'grey' (cf. Got. *hāzs). Source: Fulk (2018), Ringe (2006).",
